      {
        "paragraph_index": 4,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insight\n\nThis dramatic enhancement is a textbook illustration of the **chelate effect**. Ethylenediamine, a bidentate ligand with two –NH₂ donor groups connected by an ethylene bridge, forms a five-membered chelate ring upon coordination to Ni²⁺. Although each individual Ni–N bond is comparable in strength to the Ni–NH₃ bond, the chelate ring closure provides a large favorable entropy contribution (releasing fewer particles from solution per donor atom coordinated), boosting the overall stability constant by ~4.6 log units. This is why chelating ligands like en are preferred in applications such as metal ion sequestration and electroplating baths.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (SRD-46)*",
